R, a powerful tool to extract and aggregate gridded datasets

This R Markdown Notebook has two distinct goals:

  • show how climatic data stored as ncdf format can easily be extracted in R;
  • illustrate how gridded data can be aggregated at a given administrative level.

Datasets

For this purpose, the gridded daily weather data for 1950-2015 available from the E-OBS repository (v13.1 at 25 km x 25km horizontal resolution) is used (Haylock et al., 2008)1.

The code chunk below reads the daily maximum temperature (tx) records from E-OBS and creates a RasterBrick i.e.a multi-layer raster object:

require(raster)
require(magrittr)
eobs.path <- "~/Desktop/EOBS/%s_0.25deg_reg_v13.1.nc"
tmax.nc <- sprintf(eobs.path, 'tx') %>%
        brick()

The analysis is performed for France at the departement level (admin 2). The shapefile (shp) comes from the Global Administrative Areas | Boundaries without limits.

ISO <- 'FRA'
shp <- getData('GADM', country = ISO, level = 2)

Grid creation

The next step is the creation of the grid for E-OBS. Therefore, a mask with non NaNs is created and extracted for locations within the shp for France. Then, coordinates are extracted from the mask and saved as SpatialPoints.

require(dplyr)
mask.EOBS <- !is.na(tmax.nc[[1]]) %>%
        crop(shp) %>%
        mask(shp)
grid.EOBS <- coordinates(mask.EOBS) %>%
    as.data.frame() %>%
    mutate(keep = getValues(mask.EOBS)) %>%
    filter(keep) %>%
    SpatialPoints()
projection(grid.EOBS) <- projection(shp)
plot(grid.EOBS, col = 'red')
plot(shp, add = T)

A lookup table is then created in which the admin levels 1 and 2 of each grid point is stored:

Time Series Extraction

The extraction of grid time series from a RasterBrick is fairly straighforward in R, by subsetting the RasterBrick with a SpatialPoints object (in this case the grid definition). This operation can be quite time consuming. The resulting data structure is a matrix, which is then transposed, converted to a data.frame (long format).

Use Case

This section contains a brief analysis of the number of critical days (\[T_\mathit{max} > 34^\circ C\]) per departement. First, the departement is added to each record (lookup.adm2).

tmax.ts.lookup

Source: local data frame [24,564,014 x 6]

         date    id  tmax  year month   departement
       (time) (int) (dbl) (dbl) (dbl)         (chr)
1  1950-01-01     1  4.91  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
2  1950-01-02     1  9.84  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
3  1950-01-03     1  9.32  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
4  1950-01-04     1  9.10  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
5  1950-01-05     1  9.18  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
6  1950-01-06     1  8.36  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
7  1950-01-07     1 10.68  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
8  1950-01-08     1  7.99  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
9  1950-01-09     1  8.30  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
10 1950-01-10     1  9.88  1950     1 Pas-de-Calais
..        ...   ...   ...   ...   ...           ...
threshold <- 34.  # degC

crit.days <- tmax.ts.lookup %>%
    group_by(year, id, departement) %>%
    summarise(N = sum(tmax > threshold)) %>%
    ungroup() %>%
    group_by(year, departement) %>%
    summarise(N.avg = mean(N))

The map below shows the average number of critical days per departement:

require(ggplot2)
require(maptools)
shp.ggplot <- shp %>%
    fortify(region = 'NAME_2') %>%
    rename(departement = id)
dat.plot <- crit.days %>%
    group_by(departement) %>%
    summarise(N.avg = mean(N.avg)) %>%
    right_join(shp.ggplot)
Joining by: "departement"
ggplot(dat.plot) + 
    aes(long, lat, group = group, fill = N.avg) + 
    geom_polygon() +
    geom_path(color = "white") +
    scale_fill_gradient(low = 'grey', high = 'darkred') +
    theme_void()

The histogram below shows the distribution of critical days:

ggplot(crit.days,  aes(x = year, y = N.avg, fill = departement)) +
    geom_bar(stat="identity") +
    theme_bw() +
    theme(legend.position="none") +
    xlab('') +
    ylab('# critical days')
